@jkff Here's another attempt. I applied your suggestion to throw CannotProvideCoderException. 

The basic idea is to throw it further in places where we cannot handle the exception. However, there are places where doing so would imply the need of declaring the exception not only in Source class but in other abstract classes too (see the extend() method in Read.java, SparkUnboundedSource.java or UnboundedReadFromBoundedSource.java classes). I found it messy because it would spread the exception everywhere. Besides that, in StateSpecFunctions.java we cannot add the throws clause because the class is implementing external API which we cannot modify. 

In those places I decided to rethrow the exception as RuntimeException as I've found no better way of dealing with it in such situations. It's far more better from passing null coder because it provides a meaningful exception message in case of no default coder.  Let me know if you agree with this solution.
